Project Context for Copilot The goal of this script is to train a supervised machine learning classifier that categorizes the sentiment of unstructured text (YouTube comments) into three classes: negative (0), neutral (1), and positive (2). The system must utilize MLOps best practices, specifically addressing training-serving skew, class imbalance, and strict experiment tracking using MLflow.
1. Pipeline Architecture & Feature Engineering
To eliminate the training-serving skew discovered in our MVP, the feature extraction and classification steps must be bundled.
Pipeline Construction: You must use sklearn.pipeline.Pipeline (or imblearn.pipeline.Pipeline if implementing SMOTE) to combine the vectorizer and the classifier into a single deployable artifact.
Text Vectorization: The first step in the pipeline must be a TfidfVectorizer configured with max_features=5000, ngram_range=(1,2), and stop_words="english"
.
2. Training Strategy & Class Imbalance
We are dealing with imperfect proxy labels engineered from YouTube video metrics, which introduces the risk of Proxy Over-optimization where the model learns to maximize a proxy rather than the true objective
.
Data Sourcing: The script should be configured to primarily train on our supplementary Reddit sentiment dataset, which contains verified ground-truth labels, rather than exclusively relying on the engineered YouTube "likes per 100 views" target variable.
Algorithm Selection: The script must train and evaluate three different classifiers: XGBClassifier, LGBMClassifier, and LinearSVC
.
Class Imbalance Handling: Sentiment data frequently suffers from severe class imbalance, which can skew precision and recall if ignored
. The training loop must actively handle this by integrating SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique) or by dynamically adjusting class weights within the model parameters
.
3. ModelOps: Experiment Tracking with MLflow
All model training must be systematically tracked to ensure reproducibility and proper performance comparison.
Run Isolation: Each model's training process must be wrapped in its own mlflow.start_run(run_name="Model_Name") block
.
Parameter Logging: You must log all relevant hyperparameters for each model, such as learning_rate, max_depth, n_estimators, and objective
.
Artifact Logging: Upon completion of training, the entire fitted Pipeline object (containing both the TfidfVectorizer and the classifier) must be serialized and logged to MLflow as the model artifact.
4. Technical Evaluation Metrics
The script must evaluate the model's performance on a holdout test set to ensure it generalizes well to unseen data.
Metric Calculation: Compute and log the Weighted F1 Score, Precision, and Recall for each experiment
. The primary metric for comparison will be the Weighted F1 score
.
True Evaluation Framework: The script must be designed to evaluate the pipeline against a small, manually hand-labeled test set of actual YouTube comments. Evaluating solely against our engineered proxy labels only tests how well the model guesses a video's overall like-to-view ratio, not the actual text sentiment. As noted in industry case studies, offline model performance metrics like F1 or RMSE are merely a "health check" to ensure the algorithm functions mathematically; true value requires robust evaluation against accurate ground truth
.
5. Model Selection & Registry
Once the three pipelines have been trained and evaluated, the script must automate the staging of the best model.
Champion Selection: Programmatically sort the tracked runs by their Weighted F1 Score in descending order and isolate the top-performing model
.
Registry Push: Push the winning pipeline artifact to the local MLflow Model Registry under the exact name YouTube_Sentiment_Champion
. Ensure the code assigns an alias of champion to this specific version to make API retrieval easier
.